Today, I voted to keep our government open and serving the American people while supporting efforts to return Congress to regular funding procedures. This short-term, clean funding resolution prevents harmful disruptions to our national security and ensures that vital federal programs remain open for Northern Ohioans and Americans across the country.

This funding resolution also includes my OMUFA Act, which improves access to over-the-counter medicines. With today’s passage of this funding resolution, we can now move forward on fiscal year 2026 appropriations negotiations without disrupting any government programs.

Today marks 24 years since the September 11th terrorist attacks that changed our nation forever. On that morning, 2,977 innocent lives were taken, and countless families were left with heartbreak, and every American reeled in communal pain. We remember the bravery of the first responders who ran toward dangers when others were fleeing, and the courage of Americans who died as heroes aboard Flight 93. Their sacrifice and selflessness will never be forgotten.

Nearly a quarter century later, the memories of that day are still vivid for those who lived through it. We remember where we were, how we felt, and how in the days that followed, Americans came together with strength and unity in the face of evil.

As we honor those we lost 24 years ago today, let us keep their families in our prayers, express gratitude to the men and women who continue to defend our freedoms, and remember what it means to be American. We will never forget.

#OTD in 1813, the Battle of Lake Erie took place. At the start of the War of 1812, the British navy controlled Lake Erie unchallenged. That changed on September 10, 1813, when American forces under Oliver H. Perry defeated Robert H. Barclay’s fleet off South Bass Island.

This decisive victory kept Lake Erie in American hands for the remainder of the war and stopped any potential British invasion of Ohio and Pennsylvania from Canada.

Fun #OH5 Fact: The Spirit of ’76, the famous oil painting depicting a flag bearer, a drummer boy, and fifer marching across a battlefield during the American Revolution, was created by Archibald Willard of Wellington, Ohio, which is located in Lorain County, in the Fifth Congressional District.

Originally titled Yankee Doodle, the painting was begun by Willard at his home in Wellington and was exhibited at the 1876 Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia.

Now located in Marblehead, Massachusetts, this painting continues to embody the spirit of Americana and patriotism, capturing the resilience and unity that helped shape our nation’s founding.

In an 1826 letter – the last he ever wrote - Thomas Jefferson spoke of the importance of Independence Day. “For ourselves, let the annual return of this day forever refresh our recollections of these rights, and an undiminished devotion to them,” he said.

Happy Independence Day! Today, we celebrate the anniversary of our independence and honor the brave individuals who fought for our freedom. The United States is rich in history and traditions. John Adams once envisioned that the Fourth of July would be celebrated with “pomp and parade, with shows, games, sports, guns, bells, bonfires and illuminations from one end of this continent to the other from this time forward forever more.” With that spirit in mind, I hope you enjoy a safe and joyful celebration with your family, friends, and community.

Last Friday was National Manufacturing Day, and I was able to stop by two manufacturing plants located in Findlay, OH: Kreate and Ball Corporation. These are just two of the more than 1,000 manufacturers located in Ohio’s Fifth District. 

I’m going to continue working in Congress to advance policies that support our manufacturing industry and the thousands of jobs they provide for Ohioans.

Marcia and I are saddened to learn of former U.S. Rep. David Hobson’s passing. From 1991 to 2009, David faithfully represented the people of Ohio’s 7th Congressional District. Prior to being elected to Congress, David served in the Ohio National Guard and served for nearly a decade in the Ohio Senate. We extend our heartfelt sympathies to the Hobson family as they grieve this loss.
